Programming in R

These notes are based on Chapter 3-5 of JMR — Jones, O., Maillardet, R., & Robinson, A. (2009). Introduction to scientific programming and simulation using R. CRC Press.

for loop

JMR 3.9.2

Let \(h(x,n) = 1 + x + x^2+\dots+ x^n = \sum_{i=0}^n x^i\). Write an R program to calculate \(h(x,n)\) using for loop.

h <- function(x,n) {
  sum <- 0
  for (i in 0:n) {
    sum <- sum + x^i
  }
  return(sum)
}

JMR 3.9.3

The function \(h(x,n)\) from JMR 3.9.2 is the finite sum of a geometric sequence. It has the following explicit formula, for \(x\neq1\), \[ h(x,n) = \frac{1-x^{n+1}}{1-x} .\] Test your program from JMR 3.9.2 against this formula using the following values

\(x\) \(n\) \(h(x,n)\) \(\frac{1-x^{n+1}}{1-x}\)
0.3 55 1.4285714 1.4285714
6.6 8 4.243335510^{6} 4.243335510^{6}

You may use format(h(6.6,8), scientific=FALSE) for a nicer look.

while loop

JMR 3.9.4

First write a program that achieves the same result as in JMR 3.9.2 but using a while loop. Then write a program that does this using vector operations (and no loops).

h2 <- function(x,n) {
  sum <- 0
  i <- 0
  while (i <= n) {
    sum <- sum + x^i
    i <- i + 1
  }
  return(sum)
}
x <- 6.6
n <- 8
h2(x,n)
## [1] 4243336
sum(x^(1:n)) # Just one line!
## [1] 4243335

Vector operations are faster and cool. We should use them when performance is required (e.g., Size of the Mandelbrot set). But, if they run for a second or two, I recommend using loops to be explicit about what you are doing.

if statement

Are you prime?

Write a function that returns whether an integer \(n\geq2\) is prime. (Recall that \(n\geq2\) is prime if it has only two factors: \(1\) and \(n\).)

prime <- function(n) {
  if (n > 2){
    for (m in 2:(n/2)) {
    # for (m in 2:(sqrt(n))) {
      if (n %% m == 0) {
        return(FALSE)
      }
    }
  }
  return(TRUE)
}
prime(7)
## [1] TRUE

We may replace n/2 with sqrt(n) and make it more efficient because if \(n=m_1m_2\), at least one of \(m_1\) and \(m_2\) must be less than or equal to \(\sqrt{n}\).

JMR 3.9.8

How does program provided in JMR p.32 behave if a2=0 and/or a1=0? Using if statements, modify the program so that it gives sensible answers for all possible (numerical) inputs.

a2 <- 0
a1 <- 2
a0 <- 1
discrim <- a1^2 - 4*a2*a0
if (discrim > 0) {
  roots <- c( (-a1 + sqrt(a1^2 - 4*a2*a0))/(2*a2),
              (-a1 - sqrt(a1^2 - 4*a2*a0))/(2*a2) )
} else {
  if (discrim == 0) {
    roots <- -a1/(2*a2)
  } else {
    roots <- c()
  }
}
roots
## [1]  NaN -Inf

When using the quadratic formula, a problematic case is a2=0, which makes the function no longer quadratic but linear. So, let’s separate this case using if.

if (a2 != 0) {
  if (discrim > 0) {
    roots <- c( (-a1 + sqrt(a1^2 - 4*a2*a0))/(2*a2),
                (-a1 - sqrt(a1^2 - 4*a2*a0))/(2*a2) )
  } else {
    if (discrim == 0) {
      roots <- -a1/(2*a2)
    } else {
      roots <- c()
    }
  }
} else if (a1 != 0) {
  roots <- -a0/a1
} else {
  roots <- c()
}
roots
## [1] -0.5

Plotting

For practice, let’s draw a hyperbolic tangent with three fixed points at \(x = 0, \pm1.915\). \[y = 2\tanh(x) = 2\frac{e^{x}-e^{-x}}{e^{x}+e^{-x}}\]

x <- c(-1.915,0,1.915)
y <- c(-1.915,0,1.915)
plot(x, y, pch = 19, xlim=c(-2,2), ylim=c(-2,2))
title(expression(y==2*tanh(x)))
curve(2*tanh(x), from=-3, to=3, add=TRUE)
curve(x*1, from=-3, to=3, add=TRUE)
text(-1.55, -.8, "fixed point at -1.915")
text(0, -.2, "fixed point at 0", pos=4)
text(1.55, .8, "fixed point at 1.915")
arrows(-1.8, -1, -1.9, -1.8, length=0.1)
arrows(1.8, 1, 1.9, 1.8, length=0.1)

R Markdown

These notes are based on Xie, Y., Allaire, J. J., & Grolemund, G. (2018). R markdown: The definitive guide. CRC Press.

Markdown syntax

To me, the Markdown motto is “Simplistic yet good enough”. Don’t forget to use line breaks generously to avoid unintended outputs. The following are some of Markdown syntax of heavy use.

Headings

Just like Microsoft Word, headings in Markdown not only produce section titles but also help to generate TOC (table of contents). For example, this section has a third-level header (### Headings), which appears in TOC.

List

Start each item with - followed by a space at a line. For example,

- Item 1
- Item 2
- ...

produces

  • Item 1
  • Item 2
  • …

Link

To attach a “url” to a “text”, write [text](url). For example,

[The University of Melbourne](https://www.unimelb.edu.au)

produces The University of Melbourne.

An image is inserted in a similar way. For example, ![](images/rstudio.png) (i.e., adding ! in front). We often leave empty inside the brackets [ ].

Indentation

Just use > and a space . For example,

> This is indented.

produces

This is indented.

Code

Inline code is produced by putting code inside ` ` like `code here`.

YAML meta data

YAML (a recursive acronym for “YAML Ain’t Markup Language”) is used at the top of R Markdown script for a header that specifies meta data for the document. This document’s YAML header looks as follows.

---
title: "R, RStudio and R Markdown"
author: |
  |
  | Yuji Saikai
  | ysaikai@unimelb.edu.au
  | School of Mathematics and Statistics
  | The University of Melbourne
output:
  html_document:
    toc: true
    toc_float: true
    code_folding: show
    css: styles.css
---

Code chunks

This is where R code is written. A code chunk may look as follows.

```{r}
x <- 5 # 1st line of your R code.
y <- x^2 # 2nd line of your R code.
```

Conveniently, we can run the code without leaving the Markdown script. Just put the cursor somewhere in the chunk and press Cmd + Shift + Return (Ctrl + Shift + Enter on Linux and Windows).

We can provide many parameters inside {r} to specify how the code behaves and is itself displayed in the generated document. For example, {r, include=FALSE} means that the code is run but nothing shows up in the document.

Besides code chunks, we can also insert values of R objects and one-line computation as an inline text. A consequence is that we need not and indeed should not separately copy and paste results of our analysis. For example, a sentence “It predicts the score equal to 97.” should be written as:

It predicts the score equal to `r x`.

where the value 97 is stored in x. If we update the analysis thereby the value of x (e.g., x=97 to x=88), then the value in the output document will be automatically updated. This is a key feature of R Markdown for “reproducibility”, an idea much advocated in scientific communities. (See replication crisis.)

We use this feature in JMR 3.9.3 above. To render the table, the source has

| $x$ | $n$ | $h(x,n)$ | $\frac{1-x^{n+1}}{1-x}$ |
| ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| 0.3 | 55 | `r h(.3,55)` | `r (1-.3^56)/(1-.3)` |
| 6.6 | 8 | `r h(6.6,8)` | `r (1-6.6^9)/(1-6.6)` |

Much more detais are found here.
